Intro & Reflection  
My visual argument addresses the unrealistic beauty standards and pressures that society puts on women. These unrealistic expectations are perpetuated through media, advertising, and societal norms and are a constant source of noise. These expectations can cause negative effects on mental-health, self-esteem and identity. In my visual argument I want to relay the emotions and hurt women feel trying to conform themselves and the things they will do.  
![][image1]  
My main inspiration for this image came from an older newspaper I found that was titled “The New Beauty-Culture”. While trying to find the best place for it in the image, I got the idea to turn the word culture into cult. I made a hand drawn x over the last part of the word and this made the change more personal. Calling it a cult is apt because people will give anything to fit these standards and it can take over one's life.   
![][image2]  
I wanted to include a measuring tape because measurements and numbers are such a large focus with beauty standards. Societal ideals have a goal weight, waist size, height and essentially anything on one's body.  Those obsessed with body image get focused on body measurements and numbers. The measuring tape is positioned to cross over the body, centering on the neck, representing how suffocating it can be worrying about fitting into these standards.   
![][image3]  
The background of the image is a mannequin, this represents the unrealistic ideals for women. Mannequins are supposed to reflect a body, but the measurements and look of a mannequin are very unrealistic. The mannequin also does not have distinctive facial features which is a critique on society. Beauty standards try to make everyone be the same and do not value uniqueness and being your own person. Someone’s face is the most personal aspect to them and by taking away those identifying features you dehumanize them.
